      <p>1. <strong>Cooktop Not Turning On</strong>: This is one of the most frequent problems users encounter with induction
        cooktops. Often, the issue is related to power supply problems, such as a tripped circuit breaker or a loose plug.
        Other times, it could be due to the cooktop's internal electronics failing. Users should first check the power
        connection and reset the breaker if necessary. If the cooktop still doesn't turn on, it may require professional
        repair or replacement of internal components.</p>
      <p>2. <strong>Inconsistent Heating</strong>: Induction cooktops are prized for their precise temperature control, but
        sometimes users may find that the heating is uneven or fluctuates. This can result from using incompatible cookware,
        as induction cooktops require magnetic-based pots and pans to function correctly. Another cause could be a dirty or
        damaged cooktop surface interfering with the magnetic field. Ensuring that the cookware is induction-compatible and
        keeping the cooktop clean can often resolve this issue.</p>
      <p>3. <strong>Error Codes Displayed</strong>: Modern induction cooktops come equipped with digital displays that show
        error codes when there is a malfunction. These codes can indicate various issues, such as overheating, sensor
        malfunction, or power supply problems. Each code corresponds to a specific problem, which can usually be found in the
        user manual. Addressing these error codes promptly is essential to prevent further damage and ensure the cooktop
        operates efficiently.</p>
      <p>4. <strong>Cookware Not Detected</strong>: Induction cooktops rely on magnetic detection to heat cookware. If the
        cooktop fails to detect the pot or pan, it won't heat up. This problem often arises when using cookware that is not
        induction-compatible or has a warped bottom that doesn't make proper contact with the cooktop surface. To resolve
        this, users should ensure their cookware is marked as induction-compatible and has a flat, stable base. Additionally,
        the pot or pan should be properly centered on the cooking zone.</p>
      <p>5. <strong>Noise During Operation</strong>: While induction cooktops are generally quieter than gas or electric
        stoves, they can sometimes produce a humming or buzzing noise during operation. This noise is usually caused by the
        electromagnetic energy interacting with the cookware. Lightweight or thin pans can exacerbate this issue. Using
        heavier, high-quality cookware can help minimize the noise. If the noise is unusually loud or persistent, it could
        indicate a problem with the internal components of the cooktop and may require professional inspection.</p>
      <p>6. <strong>Surface Cracks or Damage</strong>: The glass-ceramic surface of an induction cooktop is durable but not
        impervious to damage. Heavy impacts or thermal shocks can cause cracks or scratches, compromising the cooktop's
        efficiency and safety. To prevent this, users should avoid dropping heavy objects on the surface and ensure that hot
        cookware is not placed on cold areas of the cooktop. If damage occurs, it often necessitates professional repair or
        replacement of the glass surface to restore the cooktop's functionality and safety.</p>
      <p>7. <strong>Overheating Issues</strong>: Induction cooktops have built-in sensors to prevent overheating, but these
        sensors can sometimes malfunction or be overly sensitive, causing the cooktop to shut down unexpectedly. Overheating
        can also occur if the ventilation around the cooktop is inadequate, preventing proper air circulation. Users should
        ensure that the cooktop is installed with sufficient clearance and that vents are not blocked. Regular maintenance and
        cleaning of the cooktop can also help prevent overheating issues.</p>
