      <h2>Induction Cooktop Maintenance</h2>
      <p>Maintaining your induction cooktop is essential for ensuring its longevity and optimal performance. Here are some
        detailed tips and best practices for keeping your induction cooktop in top condition:</p>
      <p>Regular Cleaning</p>
      <p>1. <strong>Daily Wipe Down</strong>:</p>
      <p> - After each use, allow the cooktop to cool down completely.</p>
      <p> - Use a soft, damp cloth or sponge to wipe away any spills or splatters.</p>
      <p> - For tougher stains, use a specialized induction cooktop cleaner or a mild dish soap solution.</p>
      <p>2. <strong>Avoid Abrasives</strong>:</p>
      <p> - Do not use abrasive sponges, steel wool, or harsh chemical cleaners as they can scratch the glass surface.</p>
      <p> - For stubborn stains, a plastic or silicone scraper can be used gently.</p>
      <p>Deep Cleaning</p>
      <p>1. <strong>Weekly Maintenance</strong>:</p>
      <p> - Once a week, give your cooktop a more thorough cleaning.</p>
      <p> - Apply a small amount of cooktop cleaner to the surface and spread it with a soft cloth.</p>
      <p> - Let it sit for a few minutes to break down any residue, then buff it out with a clean, dry cloth.</p>
      <p>2. <strong>Cleaning Around the Edges</strong>:</p>
      <p> - Pay attention to the edges and corners where grime can accumulate.</p>
      <p> - Use a cotton swab or a soft brush dipped in a mild cleaning solution to clean these areas.</p>
      <p>Component Care</p>
      <p>1. <strong>Cooling Fans</strong>:</p>
      <p> - Ensure the cooling fans are not obstructed and are working efficiently.</p>
      <p> - Periodically check the vents for dust and debris. Use a soft brush or compressed air to clean them.</p>
      <p>2. <strong>Induction Coils</strong>:</p>
      <p> - While the induction coils themselves are not directly accessible, keeping the cooktop surface clean helps prevent
        any issues with the coils.</p>
      <p> - If you notice any irregular heating or noise, it might be a sign that the coils need professional inspection.</p>
      <p>Proper Usage</p>
